I am a parent of a child with a disability.  In order for him to grow up to be a productive citizen, it is absolutely essential that he receive therapy (speech and occupational therapy, especially).  Even though we homeschool him, he receives therapy at the local elementary school, however, the therapy he receives at school is not enough.  He currently qualifies for, receives, and needs private speech and language therapy and occupational therapy.  Because of the therapy he receives, and because I work so hard with him at home, he is currently achieving and retaining knowledge at a faster rate than his normally developing peers.  He will never catch up with his normally developing peers, but he will be able to hold down gainful employment at his current rate of achievement.  If the budget cuts which are being considered by the NC General Assembly are passed, our son will not be able to receive these services through Medicaid and we cannot afford to pay for them privately.  That means our son may not grow up to be a productive, tax-paying citizen.  Please consider the long-term consequences of cutting these necessary (and federally mandated) services.

Another negative consequence is the effect these cuts will have on the therapists and their ability to stay gainfully employed.  I fail to see how putting more people on the unemployment rolls will help our economy.

Respectfully,
